   <h2>Gastona on Android</h2>

   <p>
      For desktop the way of running a gastona script is passing it as parameter to gastona.jar.
      But this is not a practical approach for an android App.
   </p>

   <h3>Directory /mnt/sdcard/gastona</h3>
   <p>
      This directory is where all gastona scripts (files with extension .gast) should be placed. It is possible
      to create sub directories inside of it if desired. Note that the directory and its files will remain after
      each Gastona update and also even if Gastona is uninstalled.
   </p>

   <p>
      So the first step to start running your scripts in Gastona is to create this directory. If you do it by
      pressing the button "Create gastona dir" some useful scripts will be copied to the directory as well.
   </p>

   <p>
      Some of the scripts belong to a mini tutorial and in particular three of them are actually
      powerful tools that makes the process of programming your android device easy.
   </p>

   <h3>/mnt/sdcard/gastona/autoStart.gast</h3>

   <p>
      Always Gastona App will execute this script if found. In its default version this script
      is a explorer and launcher of the rest of scripts in /mnt/sdcard/gastona. Since it is the
      start of all scripts it is recomended not to change it at the beginning unless you know how
      to restore it in case things don't work as expected.
   </p>

   <h3>File Ciervo</h3>

   <p>
      This, less than 200 lines script is an amazing File server. With it you can explore from
      your PC all files of your android device and also copy them to your PC (download).
   </p>

   <p>
      This script acts as a small http server so a connection, for example via WiFi, between your PC
      and your android device is needed. Also you need to know the IP address or the host name that
      the android device has in your network. Once you have all this:
   </p>

      <ul>
      <li> Launch File Ciervo on android</li>
      <li> Open a browser in your PC and introduce the url http://(android ip):7878</li>
      </ul>

   <p>
      Now the interesting part actually occurs in your browser where you can navigate through your android
      file structure. On your device you will see lost of messages. That just indicates the activity of
      the http command involved and it might be useful to check if the connection is doing well.
   </p>

   <h3>ProgramMe</h3>

   <p>
      This script also connects your android device with your PC in a similar way to File Ciervo.
      This time oriented to handle and transfer your gastona scripts from and to your android device!
      Once you have running ProgramMe on your android device connect to it from your browser 
      using the port 7676, then you can
   </p>
      <ul>
      <li> Load scripts from the android device into the browser (PC)</li>
      <li> Edit scripts directly in the browser</li>
      <li> Run scripts into the device from the browser</li>
      <li> Save scripts into the device from the browser</li>
      </ul>
   <p>
      That is, almost full controll of your scripts using a browser.
   </p>

   <h3>About obtaining the IP address</h3>

   <p>
      Depending on the network configuration it might be more or less difficult to get it. If available,
      the host name of the device in the network is more convenient than the IP since it will not change
      so you can store the final url in your browser favorites and connect the next time just with a click.
   </p>

